Plotting mtcars

Base R Plotting

We begin by exploring the base plotting functions of R and see what that looks like. In order to break out the category of cyl properly, well need to classify it as a factor variable instead of an integer. This allows us to plot it as a discrete variable instead of continuous.

Plotting with ggplot

Well recreate the same metrics by plotting the same things, this time using ggplot.

Proper Grammar and Data Format

When plotting, its important to have things laid out properly so that it makes intuitive sense to us when we go back and read it, or just want the code to make sense.

An effective way to plot, but ultimately not proper.

Why is this improper? One of the reasons is the lack of legend. Lets dive in.

Variables that we have with this

str(iris)
## Classes 'tbl_df', 'tbl' and 'data.frame':    150 obs. of  5 variables:

Weve got 4 variables plotted and a total of 5 variables in the set. Well want to rearrange the data to define variables according to what were interested in.

Originally, we set up Length on the x-axis, for both the Sepal and Petal, and then Width on the y-axis. A better way to rearrange this would be to have a length and width column (aka variable) and add a new variable Part to define which part of the flower were looking at.

Tidying Up Iris Dataset

In order to properly explore the dataset, its easier if we turn a wide dataset into long form. This means taking some of the variables and turning them into categories of a single variable.

For example, instead of having Sepal.Length and Sepal.Width, well make a column that has the Value, and another column describing which Part were looking at - Sepal or Width.

Primer with TIDYR

The gather() function from tidyr rearranges the dataframe by specifying the columns that are categorical and splitting the Value pairs amongst the different categories.

Essentially gather() goes from the original structure:

Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
5.1 3.5 1.4 0.2 setosa

And rearranges to:

Key Value Species
Sepal.Length 5.1 setosa
Sepal.Width 3.5 setosa

The separate() function allows us split the new key column. However, since the names had two variables within each (Width and Length), well split those up by telling separate to look for the . and split the respective value into each new column. The new columns were creating are Part and Measure.

Lets see it in action.

Plotting with a Wide Dataset

To make the dataset wide, well move the categorical variables into a single column, but still leave Width and Length as their own. One step of keeping this tidy will be to add a unique identifier which well call Flower. By doing this before rearranging the data, were able to keep track of which flower the information came from.

Well treat Flower and Species as both categorical, and then we separate similar to before. The only difference is now well use spread() to take one of the variables we just created (Measure) and split up the categories within (for us, Width and Length) and add in their values.

Discussing Aesthetics

Its important to note that aesthetics is not describing the appearance of the graph - that is attributes! Rather, we are describing the way the data is represented. Are we showing weight vs height? Or grouping a specific category together? These can all be accomplished through the initial aes() call with x, y, color, fill, size, alpha, labels, and shape.

Below, the 4 different graphs show an exploration of how we are changing the aesthetics by changing which variables get mapped to which aesthetic. For example, the first plot has mpg mapped to the x axis and cyl to the y.

Now if we explore how to change the looks (attributes) of the graph to make it more appealing and easier to understand, we can experiment with the fill and color.

Note that on plot #2, we mapped a categorical variable to fill (cyl), but nothing happened. This is because when using geom_point(), there is no fill attribute for it, only a color outline. We can change the type of point were using (shape = 21), but it just takes knowledge of which shapes have a fill color attribute to them.

Well explore just a little more, but this time changing the way the cylinder aesthetic is mapped onto the plot.

Well be exploring it through size, alpha, shape, or label.

# Map cyl to size
ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg, size = cyl)) +
    geom_point()

# Map cyl to alpha
ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg, alpha = cyl)) +
    geom_point()

# Map cyl to shape 
ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg, shape = cyl)) +
    geom_point()

# Map cyl to labels
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = wt, y = mpg, label = cyl)) +
    geom_text()

Discussing Attributes

Above we were mapping attributes to the aesthetics. This time, we are, instead, going to be looking at how to change the different attributes of the plots.

WARNING: Attributes can overwrite the aesthetics of our plot

For example, if we wanted a specific category of the plot to take on custom colors, we might specify the color with a hex code #123456. But we have to be careful of overwriting the category.

# Define a hexadecimal color
my_color <- "#123456"

# Set the color aesthetic 
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = wt, y = mpg, col = cyl)) +
    geom_point()

# Set the color aesthetic and attribute 
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = wt, y = mpg, col = cyl)) +
    geom_point(col = my_color)

# Set the fill aesthetic and color, size and shape attributes
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = wt, y = mpg, fill = cyl)) +
    geom_point(size = 10, shape = 23, col = my_color)

This helps us to start understand that we can add a lot of different features onto a plot. This can help to display some complex data. However, our brains cannot always comprehend everything we show on a plot at once.

Below is an example of what happens when we try and do too much. Note that we can still read the plot, but it takes significantly longer to comprehend whats going on.

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg,
                   y = qsec,
                   col = factor(cyl),
                   shape = factor(am),
                   size = (hp/wt))) +
  geom_point()

Position of Graphics

When plotting a scatter plot, we tend to see overplotting - two points occupy the same space on the graph. To help visually show the data better, we can add some jitter to the plot, which just adds some noise.

Plotting bar graphs can be similar. We set the how the bars are displayed by setting the position within the geom_bar() call. The default for bar graphs is position = "stack". Below shows how the different positions of the data can help us to understand whats really going on, better.

cyl.am <- ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = factor(cyl), fill = factor(am)))

## Adding the base geom_bar() call
cyl.am + geom_bar()

## Now using fill to show proportion (take note of the axis)
cyl.am +
  geom_bar(position = "fill")

## Dodge shows difference by similarity and proximity
cyl.am +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge")

## Looks good. Clean it up with nice axes and scales
val = c("#e41a1c", "#377eb8")
lab = c("Manual", "Automatic")
cyl.am +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  scale_x_discrete("Cylinders") +
  scale_y_continuous("Number") +
  scale_fill_manual("Transmission",
                    values = val,
                    labels = lab)

Making a Dummy Aesthetic

When we dont want to have a labeled y-axis, we just want a placeholder to help visually show our data. For example, if we just wanted to show what the mpg for each entry in our mtcars dataset, without comparing it to anything, well need to force a y-axis to it.

## The excercises have us define a new column in the dataset like below
mtcars$group <- 0

## But it'll be easier if we ignore that and not unnecessarily clutter our data
## Instead, the dummy variable is set when plotting x vs y
ggplot(mtcars, aes(mpg, 0)) +
  geom_jitter()

## To change the y-limits to zoom out a little
ggplot(mtcars, aes(mpg, 0)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(-2,2))

Overplotting

When we are dealing with large datasets or perhaps discrete values of data, the points will overlap. We see this happening most often when using a scatter plot. It can be easy to just make a quick scatter plot, without worrying about the amount of points were actually seeing.

Some of the reasons we may be dealing with overplotting is the follows:

  1. Large datasets
  2. Imprecise data where the points are not clearly separated
  3. Interval data (i.e.data appears at fixed values)
  4. Aligned data values on a single axis

To explore some of the issues and solutions involved when plotting these kinds of data points, well need a few techniques to help show what the data is actually telling us.

Point, Shape, & Transparency

Overplotting means we have too many points on one plot. This can be alleviated by changing the type of shapes were using.

First, this is what a base plot looks like without any modifications. Note: we are using the mtcars for this.

ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg, col = cyl)) +
    geom_point(size = 4)

Nice. A little hard to tell whats going on here, but we dont really know what were missing actually. Instead of using solid shapes/points, well instead use a hollow shape.

We can achieve this by telling the geom_point() to use shape = 1.

It looks like we didnt miss out on too much. Still - helpful to know whats going on.

Another technique is to change the transparency or alpha. For alpha to work , 0 is completely transparent, while 1 is fully filled in. Well change the shape back to default but set alpha = 0.6.

Doesnt seem to tell us all too much, but interesting nonetheless.

Alpha and Large Datasets

This time well be looking at the diamonds dataset provided to us through ggplot. Its a much larger dataset, so well experience some different issues this time.

First, if we just look at how the price changes based on the carat of the diamond, and then color by clarity, well see all the data.

diamonds <- tbl_df(diamonds)
ggplot(diamonds, aes(carat, price, col = clarity)) +
    geom_point()

There are definitely more data points here than before. Still easy to make out the trends for the most part, but if we change the transparency, well start seeing how the alpha really helps. The values will be more filled in when there are more data points that are of equal value.

Lets set alpha = 0.5.

Seems to help a bit. Not the greatest representation, but you can begin to understand how this helps.

Lets switch to another cause for overplotting: aligned data on a single axis.

To explore this, well look at clarity(x) vs.carat(y), and color by price. Because clarity only has 8 possible values it could hold, the points will only occupy 8 spots on the x-axis, while being distributed throughout the y-axis. This will certainly cause a bit confusion when viewing the plot.

Also, because we know its a large dataset, well preemptively set alpha = 0.5.

ggplot(diamonds, aes(clarity, carat, col = price)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.5)

Looks good, and you should be able to understand what aligned data on a single axis means now. Since it is aligned on one axis, its all in a straight line, making it difficult to see every different point and their respective price color.

We can add more noise to it by adding jitter: position = "jitter".

ggplot(diamonds, aes(clarity, carat, col = price)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.5, position = "jitter")

Excellent! And with that, we have completed this section!
